Third program's code:

public static void main(String[] args) {
    Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
    String word = in.next();
    int uppercase = 0;
    int lowercase = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < word.length(); i++) {
        char ch = word.charAt(i);
        if (Character.isUpperCase(ch)) {
            uppercase++;
        } else {
            lowercase++;
        }
    } if (uppercase > lowercase) System.out.println(word.toUpperCase());
    else if (lowercase > uppercase) System.out.println(word.toLowerCase());
    else System.out.println(word.toLowerCase());
} So, for a single character that is a digit (like '6'), the loop runs once. The character is not uppercase or lowercase, so the else clause (lowercase +=1). Wait, no: the code says else { lowercase++ }, but that's only if it's not uppercase.
